 Vittorio|authorlink=|year=2001|title=Wings Beneath the Sea: The Aviation Archaeology of Catalina Flying Boats in Darwin Harbour, Northern Territory|url=http://trove.nla.gov.au/work/33160695?selectedversion=NBD44462755|publisher=Unpublished M.A. Thesis.|location=Faculty of Law, Business and Arts, Northern Territory University.|isbn=}}\n{{refend}}\n\n{{World War II}}\n\n[[Category:Conflicts in 1942]]\n[[Category:Coral Sea]]\n[[Category:South West Pacific theatre of World War II]]\n[[Category:Battles of World War II involving Australia]]\n[[Category:Naval battles of World War II involving Australia]]\n[[Category:Naval aviation operations and battles]]\n[[Category:Northern Australia]]\n[[Category:Pacific Ocean theatre of World War II]]\n[[Category:World War II aerial operations and battles of the Pacific theatre]]\n[[Category:Military history of Japan during World War II]]\n[[Category:Battles of World War II involving Japan]]\n[[Category:Battles of World War II involving the United States]]\n[[Category:1942 in Japan]]\n[[Category:1942 in Australia]]\n[[Category:Australia\u2013Japan relations]]\n[[Category:Aerial operations and battles of World War II involving Australia]]\n[[Category:Aerial operations and battles of World War II involving Japan]]\n[[Category:Battles and operations of World War II involving Australia]]\n[[Category:Military attacks against Australia]]\n[[Category:Airstrikes conducted by Japan]]\n[[Category:Campaigns, operations and battles of World War II involving the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Battles and operations of World War II involving the Netherlands]]\n", "name_user": "Eastfarthingan", "label": "safe", "comment": "Cleaned up usingAutoEd", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/North_Western_Area_Campaign"}
{"title_page": "Tom Ince", "text_new": "{{for|the film director|Thomas H. Ince}}\n{{Use British English|date=July 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2018}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name           = Tom Ince\n| image          = Tom Ince 2014.jpg\n| image_size     = 240\n| caption        = Ince playing for [[Hull City A.F.C.|Hull City]] in 2014\n| fullname       = Thomas Christopher Ince<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thefa.com/-/media/files/thefaportal/governance-docs/registrations/february-2015.ashx |title=List of Temporary Transfers of Players under Written Contract Between 01/02/2015 and 28/02/2015 |publisher=The Football Association |format=PDF |page=14 |accessdate=13 June 2018}}</ref>\n| birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1992|1|30|df=y}}<ref>{{Hugman|23514|accessdate=26 December 2017}}</ref>\n| birth_place    = [[Stockport]], England\n| height         = {{convert|1.78|m|order=flip}}<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.premierleague.com/players/4137/Tom-Ince/overview |title=Tom Ince: Overview |publisher=Premier League |accessdate=26 December 2017}}</ref>\n| position       = [[Midfielder#Attacking midfielder|Attacking midfielder]] / [[Midfielder#Winger|Winger]] / [[Forward (association football)|Forward]]\n| currentclub    = [[Stoke City F.C.|Stoke City]]\n| clubnumber     = 7\n| youthyears1    = 2008\u20132010 | youthclubs1 = [[Liverpool F.C. Reserves and Academy|Liverpool]]\n| years1         = 2010\u20132011 | clubs1  =   [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]]                        | caps1  = 0  | goals1  = 0\n| years2         = 2010\u20132011 | clubs2  = \u2192 [[Notts County F.C.|Notts County]] (loan)           | caps2  = 6  | goals2  = 2\n| years3         = 2011\u20132014 | clubs3  =   [[Blackpool F.C.|Blackpool]]                        | caps3  = 100| goals3  = 31\n| years4         = 2014      | clubs4  = \u2192 [[Crystal Palace F.C.|Crystal Palace]] (loan)       | caps4  = 8  | goals4  = 1\n| years5         = 2014\u20132015 | clubs5  =   [[Hull City A.F.C.|Hull City]]                      | caps5  = 7  | goals5  = 0\n| years6         = 2014      | clubs6  = \u2192 [[Nottingham Forest F.C.|Nottingham Forest]] (loan) | caps6  = 6  | goals6  = 0\n| years7         = 2015      | clubs7  = \u2192 [[Derby County F.C.|Derby County]] (loan)           | caps7  = 18 | goals7  = 11\n| years8         = 2015\u20132017 | clubs8  = [[Derby County F.C.|Derby County]]                    | caps8  = 115 | goals8  = 26\n| years9         = 2017\u20132018 | clubs9  = [[Huddersfield Town A.F.C.|Huddersfield Town]]        | caps9  = 33 | goals9  = 2\n| years10        = 2018\u2013     | clubs10 = [[Stoke City F.C.|Stoke City]]                        | caps10 = 70 | goals10 = 8\n| nationalyears1 = 2009      | nationalteam1 = [[England national under-17 football team|England U17]] | nationalcaps1 = 4  | nationalgoals1 = 0\n| nationalyears2 = 2011      | nationalteam2 = [[England national under-19 football team|England U19]] | nationalcaps2 = 4  | nationalgoals2 = 0\n| nationalyears3 = 2012\u20132014 | nationalteam3 = [[England national under-21 football team|England U21]] | nationalcaps3 = 18 | nationalgoals3 = 3\n| club-update    = 19:47, 7 March 2020 (UTC)\n}}\n'''Thomas Christopher Ince''' (born 30 January 1992) is an English professional [[Association football|footballer]] who plays as either an [[Midfielder#Attacking midfielder|attacking midfielder]], [[Midfielder#Winger|winger]] or [[Forward (association football)|forward]] for {{English football updater|StokeCty}} club [[Stoke City F.C.|Stoke City]].\n\nThe son of former [[England national football team|England]] captain [[Paul Ince]], Tom Ince began his career with [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]], for whom he made his professional debut in the [[2010\u201311 Liverpool F.C. season|2010\u201311 season]], coming on as a [[Substitute (association football)|substitute]] in the [[EFL Cup|League Cup]]. He later spent time that season on loan at [[EFL League One|League One]] club [[Notts County F.C.|Notts County]], scoring twice in eight appearances. At the end of the season, Ince turned down a new contract and moved to [[Blackpool F.C.|Blackpool]], who had just been relegated from the Premier League. In two-and-a-half seasons at Blackpool, Ince played 113 games in all competitions and scored 33 goals. He also won the [[Football League Awards#2013 Awards|2013 Football League Young Player of the Year Award]] and was named in the [[PFA Team of the Year (2010s)#2012\u201313|2012\u201313]] [[PFA Team of the Year]].\n\nIn January 2014, he signed on loan for Premier League club [[Crystal Palace F.C.|Crystal Palace]], for whom he scored his first Premier League goal, and returned to the division permanently at the end of the season, joining [[Hull City A.F.C.|Hull City]] on a free transfer. Ince did not feature regularly for Hull in the [[2014\u201315 Hull City A.F.C. season|2014\u201315 season]], spending time on loan at the end of 2014 with [[Nottingham Forest F.C.|Nottingham Forest]] before returning briefly to Hull. A loan spell at the end of the season with Derby County was a success, with Ince scoring 11 goals in 18 appearances. At the end of the season, he joined Derby for a fee of \u00a34.75&nbsp;million, briefly becoming the club's most-expensive signing. Ince spent the [[2017\u201318 Huddersfield Town A.F.C. season|2017\u201318]] season with [[Huddersfield Town A.F.C.|Huddersfield Town]] before joining [[Stoke City F.C.|Stoke City]] in July 2018 for a fee of \u00a310million.\n\nInce has been capped internationally for England at [[England national under-17 football team|under-17]], [[England national under-19 football team|under-19]] and [[England national under-21 football team|under-21]] levels.\n\n==Early and personal life==\nInce was born in [[Stockport]], Greater Manchester.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.11v11.com/players/tom-ince-236317/ |title=Tom Ince |website=11v11.com |publisher=AFS Enterprises |accessdate=26 December 2017}}</ref> His father [[Paul Ince|Paul]] played professional football at a high level with England, [[Inter Milan]], [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] and [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]]. When Ince was three-years-old he moved to Italy after Paul had signed for Inter Milan where he attended an Italian school and became fluent in Italian, the family spent two years in Italy before returning to England.<ref>{{cite web |title=Paul Ince's son wants to earn his own reputation at Blackpool |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2011/dec/13/thomas-ince-paul-blackpool |website=The Guardian |accessdate=26 August 2019}}</ref>\n\nHe became a father on 11 July 2013.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/football-league/tom-ince-dad-says-i-must-leave-blackpool-to-reach-top-8729023.html |title=Tom Ince: 'Dad says I must leave Blackpool to reach top'|newspaper=The Independent|date=24 July 2013|accessdate=7 July 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Club career==\n===Liverpool===\nInce signed for [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] as a youth player in 2008 and was handed a first-team squad number (number 45) at the start of the [[2010\u201311 Liverpool F.C. season|2010\u201311 season]]. On 29 July 2010, he was an unused substitute for the first time in Liverpool's [[UEFA Europa League]] qualifier against [[FK Rabotni\u010dki]]. He made his debut for Liverpool on 22 September 2010 as a 106th-minute substitute for [[Daniel Pacheco]] in the club's third round [[EFL Cup|League Cup]] defeat to [[Northampton Town F.C.|Northampton Town]] at [[Anfield]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Liverpool 2\u20132 Northampton|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/league_cup/9010076.stm|date=22 September 2010|publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate=7 July 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn 1 November 2010, Ince linked up with his father [[Paul Ince]], who was the manager of [[EFL League One|League One]] club [[Notts County F.C.|Notts County]], signing a short-term loan deal from Liverpool until January 2011.<ref>{{cite web | date = 1 November 2010 | title=Notts Co bring Reds pair in| url =http://uk.eurosport.yahoo.com/01112010/63/notts-co-bring-reds-pair.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110101114048/http://uk.eurosport.yahoo.com/01112010/63/notts-co-bring-reds-pair.html|archivedate=1 January 2011|publisher=Yahoo! Eurosport UK|accessdate=7 July 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Duo complete loan move|url=http://www.liverpoolfc.tv/news/latest-news/duo-complete-loan-move|date=1 November 2010|publisher=Liverpool F.C. |accessdate=7 July 2014}}</ref> He signed on loan alongside 22-year-old right back [[Stephen Darby]]. Ince made his County debut on 6 November in the 2\u20130 [[FA Cup]] first round victory against [[Gateshead F.C.|Gateshead]].<ref>{{cite news | date = 6 November 2010 | title=Notts County 2\u20130 Gateshead| url =http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/fa_cup/9140357.stm | publisher =BBC Sport|accessdate=7 July 2014}}</ref> On 13 November, he made his league debut in the 3\u20131 away loss to [[Exeter City F.C.|Exeter City]]. On 11 December, Ince scored his first career goal, in County's 2\u20130 league win against [[Milton Keynes Dons F.C.|Milton Keynes Dons]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Fletcher |first=Paul |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_div_2/9254915.stm |title=Notts County 2\u20130 MK Dons |date=11 December 2010 |accessdate=7 July 2014 |publisher=BBC Sport}}</ref>\n\nAt the end of December 2010, Ince said that joining his father at Notts County had benefited him as he had \"got a bit lost\" at Liverpool, who had tried to change his style of play. He found that his father \"wanted me to be the player that I was\" and that the move had \"given me a fresher life\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/n/notts_county/9309301.stm|title=Notts County loan benefits Thomas Ince|publisher=BBC Sport|date=22 December 2010|accessdate=3 November 2015}}</ref> Ince scored for County for a second time on 3 January 2011 in a 3\u20130 win against [[Hartlepool United F.C.|Hartlepool United]] before his loan expired on 10 January and he returned to Liverpool.\n\nDespite his father's repeated attempts to re-sign his son on loan,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.tribalfootball.com/articles/county-boss-ince-wants-return-liverpool-duo-1393251|title=County boss Ince wants return of Liverpool duo|publisher=Tribal Football|date=January 2011|accessdate=3 November 2015}}</ref><ref name=countywants>{{cite news|url=http://www.nottinghampost.com/Magpies-boss-accuses-Liverpool-silly-son-s-future/story-12212432-detail/story.html|title=Magpies boss accuses Liverpool of being 'silly' over his son's future|newspaper=Nottingham Post|date=7 January 2011|accessdate=3 November 2015}}{{Dead link|date=September 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> Liverpool refused. Ince's contract expired at the end of the 2010\u201311 season and they would not let Ince go back out on loan unless he signed a new long-term contract.<ref name=countywants/> Ince's father described the contract offer as \"derisory\" and called Liverpool \"silly\" for refusing to let Ince re-join his club on loan.<ref name=countywants/> Ultimately, Ince declined to sign a new contract with Liverpool and so he left the club on a free transfer at the end of the season.\n\n===Blackpool===\n[[File:ThomasInce.jpg|thumb|upright|Ince warming up for [[Blackpool F.C.|Blackpool]] in 2011]]\n\nOn 3 August 2011, Ince signed a two-year contract with [[Blackpool F.C.|Blackpool]], with an option for a third.<ref name=blacksign>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/b/blackpool/9545631.stm |title=Blackpool sign Liverpool winger Tom Ince |date=4 August 2011 |accessdate=7 July 2014 |publisher=BBC Sport}}</ref> As Ince was under 24 years of age and had been offered a new contract by his previous club, a compensation deal had to be agreed.<ref name=blacksign/> Liverpool and Blackpool agreed an undisclosed fee and a sell-on clause which entitled Liverpool to 35% of any fee that Blackpool later received for selling Ince.<ref name=blacksign/><ref name=liverbank>{{cite news |url=http://www.liverpoolecho.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/liverpool-fc-bank-560000-windfall-8459569|title=Liverpool FC to bank \u00a3560,000 windfall from Tom Ince deal|newspaper=Liverpool Echo|date=16 January 2015|accessdate=3 November 2015}}</ref> As Blackpool had been relegated from the [[Premier League]] at the end of the [[2010\u201311 Blackpool F.C. season|2010\u201311 season]], Ince thus dropped down to the Championship to join the club, who were managed by [[Ian Holloway]].\n\nHe made his Blackpool debut in the League Cup defeat to [[Sheffield Wednesday F.C.|Sheffield Wednesday]] on 11 August 2011.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/14398745.stm |title=Sheffield Wednesday 0\u20130 Blackpool (4\u20132 penalties) |date=11 August 2011 |accessdate=11 August 2011 |publisher=BBC Sport}}</ref> He scored his first goals for Blackpool with both in a 2\u20131 win over [[Doncaster Rovers F.C.|Doncaster Rovers]] on 18 October 2011.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/15252374.stm |title=Blackpool 2\u20131 Doncaster |date=18 October 2011 |accessdate=19 October 2011 |publisher=BBC Sport}}</ref> On 25 February 2012 he scored another brace in a 3\u20131 away win against [[Bristol City F.C.|Bristol City]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/17083101 |title=Bristol City 1\u20133 Blackpool |date=25 February 2012 |accessdate=7 July 2014 |publisher=BBC Sport}}</ref> In the Championship play-off final at [[Wembley Stadium|Wembley]] on 19 May 2012, he scored an equaliser against [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham United]] but Blackpool lost the match 2\u20131.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/competitions/championship/9272841/Blackpool-v-West-Ham-United-live.html | location=London |newspaper=The Daily Telegraph | first=Thom | last=Gibbs | title=Blackpool v West Ham United: live | date=19 May 2012|accessdate=7 July 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe first League game of Blackpool's [[2012\u201313 Blackpool F.C. season|2012\u201313 season]], on 18 August 2012, saw Ince score the only goals of the game in a 2\u20130 win at [[Millwall F.C.|Millwall]]. Following the game, manager Ian Holloway revealed that Blackpool had received an offer from an unknown club, but that Ince had committed his future to ''the Seasiders'' after talking to his father. Holloway stated, \"There was interest in Tom last week. No one has heard about it but I'll share it with you. His dad wants him to stay with us.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/19322766 |title=Tom Ince advised to stay at Blackpool by father Paul, says Holloway |date=20 August 2012 |accessdate=24 August 2012 |publisher=BBC Sport}}</ref> On 7 August, he scored twice in a 6\u20130 win against [[Ipswich Town F.C.|Ipswich Town]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/19304268 |title=Blackpool 6\u20130 Ipswich|publisher=BBC Sport|date= 25 August 2012|accessdate= 18 November 2012}}</ref> In September, he scored in back-to-back games against [[Barnsley F.C.|Barnsley]] and [[Middlesbrough F.C.|Middlesbrough]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/19528053 |title=Barnsley 1\u20131 Blackpool|publisher=BBC Sport|date= 15 September 2012|accessdate= 18 November 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/19554081 |title=Blackpool 4\u20131 Middlesbrough|publisher=BBC Sport|date= 18 September 2012|accessdate= 18 November 2012}}</ref> He scored his tenth goal of the season on 3 November, completing a run of scoring in four successive games.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/20107641 |title=Derby 4\u20131 Blackpool|publisher=BBC Sport|date= 3 November 2012|accessdate=18 November 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/20134489 |title=Sheffield Wed 0\u20138 Blackpool|publisher=BBC Sport|date= 6 November 2012|accessdate= 18 November 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Cartwright |first=Phil |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/20189892 |title=Blackpool 2\u20132 Bolton|publisher= BBC Sport|date= 10 November 2012|accessdate= 18 November 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/20278348 |title=Bristol City 1\u20131 Blackpool|publisher=BBC Sport|date= 17 November 2012|accessdate= 18 November 2012}}</ref> The previous day, Holloway left Blackpool to become the new manager of [[Crystal Palace F.C.|Crystal Palace]]. [[Michael Appleton]] was appointed to replace him. In December 2012, it was reported that Ince's form was attracting the attention of his former club Liverpool, who were preparing a bid of \u00a34&nbsp;million in the January transfer window.<ref name=lpoolclosein>{{cite news|url=http://www.liverpoolecho.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/exclusive-liverpool-fc-close-4m-3327683|title=Exclusive: Liverpool FC close in on \u00a34m Tom Ince transfer|newspaper=Liverpool Echo|date=18 December 2012|accessdate=3 November 2015}}</ref> In January, Liverpool entered into negotiations with Blackpool, but ''The Seasiders''' asking price of \u00a38.5&nbsp;million proved too much for Liverpool after they had already signed [[Daniel Sturridge]] and paid off [[Joe Cole]]'s contract so they withdrew from talks.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/sport/football/transfer-news/tom-inces-move-to-liverpool-in-danger-1531140|title=In the Red: Tom Ince's move to Liverpool falling apart after fee reaches \u00a38.5m|newspaper=Daily Mirror|date=12 January 2013|accessdate=3 November 2015}}</ref> Reading made a late bid to sign him, offering a fee just below Blackpool's \u00a38m valuation<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/competitions/fa-cup/9830522/Reading-join-Liverpool-in-chase-for-Blackpools-8m-rated-Tom-Ince.html|title=Reading join Liverpool in chase for Blackpool's \u00a38m-rated Tom Ince|newspaper=The Daily Telegraph|date=16 January 2014|accessdate=30 May 2016}}</ref> the transfer window closed with Ince still at Blackpool. On 11 January 2013, Appleton resigned to become manager of [[Blackburn Rovers F.C.|Blackburn Rovers]]. He was replaced by Ince's father Paul.\n\nAt the 2013 [[Football League Awards]] on 24 March, Ince won the award for The Football League Young Player of the Year. In April 2013, after [[Wilfried Zaha]] had moved from Crystal Palace to [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] for \u00a315&nbsp;million, and with Ince the fifth-top scorer in the Championship on 18 goals, Ince's father commented that Tom should be valued at \u00a325&nbsp;million.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/22038525|title=Thomas Ince worth \u00a325m \u2013 Blackpool boss & father Paul Ince|publisher=BBC Sport|date=5 April 2013|accessdate=3 November 2015}}</ref> On 30 June 2013, Blackpool accepted what was believed to be an \u00a38&nbsp;million offer from [[Cardiff City F.C.|Cardiff City]]. It was reported that [[Swansea City A.F.C.|Swansea City]] were also interested in signing Ince, but were put off by the asking price.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/23167342 |title=Cardiff boss Malky Mackay hopeful over Tom Ince signing|publisher= BBC Sport|date= 3 July 2013|accessdate= 4 July 2013}}</ref> Despite agreeing personal terms and passing a medical with Cardiff City, Ince turned down the move on 12 July to stay in [[Blackpool]] with his newborn child.<ref>{{cite news |title=Thomas Ince: Cardiff City target to remain at Blackpool |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/23239056 |publisher=BBC Sport |date=12 July 2013 |accessdate=12 July 2013}}</ref> Aston Villa and Everton were subsequently linked with him,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.express.co.uk/sport/football/425228/Everton-to-rival-Aston-Villa-for-Blackpool-s-Tom-Ince|title=Everton to rival Aston Villa for Blackpool's Tom Ince|newspaper=Daily Express |first=Ben |last=Jefferson|date=28 August 2013|accessdate=30 May 2016}}</ref> but Ince chose to remain at Blackpool.\n\nIn his first ten league games of the [[2013\u201314 Blackpool F.C. season|2013\u201314 season]], Ince scored six goals as the team moved into fourth place in The Championship.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/24590401|title=Blackpool 2\u20132 Blackburn Rovers|publisher=BBC Sport|date=26 October 2013|accessdate=29 May 2016}}</ref> However, he then went on a lean streak and scored just one goal in his next thirteen league matches, the equaliser in a 1\u20131 draw against Leeds United on 26 December 2013.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/25441706|title=Blackpool 1\u20131 Leeds United|publisher=BBC Sport|date=26 October 2013|accessdate=26 May 2016}}</ref> In that month, Blackpool offered him a new contract, but chairman [[Karl Oyston]] expected that Ince would leave.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/25428652|title=Thomas Ince: Blackpool offer winger new contract|publisher=BBC Sport|date=18 December 2013|accessdate=26 May 2016}}</ref> On 18 January 2014, he played 90 minutes in a 2\u20130 away defeat at Barnsley.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/25692449|title=Barnsley 2\u20130 Blackpool|publisher=BBC Sport|date=18 January 2014|accessdate=26 May 2016}}</ref> It was his last game for Blackpool. During his time at the club, Ince made 113 appearances, scoring 33 goals.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/28203490|title=Tom Ince: Hull City sign Blackpool winger on two-year deal|publisher=BBC Sport|date=7 July 2014|accessdate=30 May 2016}}</ref> Three days later, his father was sacked as manager. With negotiations undergoing for Ince's transfer away from Blackpool, he was left out of the squad for their matches against Doncaster on 25 January and Reading on 28 January.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-2545848/Tom-Ince-looks-heading-Blackpool-exit-Barry-Ferguson-leaves-star-man-out.html|title=Ince looks to be heading for Blackpool exit after Ferguson leaves star man out... and the Premier League vultures are circling|newspaper=Daily Mail |first=David |last=Kent |date=25 January 2014|accessdate=26 May 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Loan to Crystal Palace===\nIn the January 2014 transfer window, numerous clubs approached Blackpool to enquire about signing Ince, who held talks with Everton, Cardiff, Newcastle, Hull City, Sunderland, Stoke City, Swansea City, Tottenham Hotspur, Crystal Palace and his former club Liverpool again.<ref name=incepoised>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/teams/blackpool/10587190/Paul-Ince-sacked-as-Blackpool-manager-with-Tom-Ince-poised-to-follow-him-out-with-move-to-Everton-or-Monaco.html|title=Paul Ince sacked as Blackpool manager with Tom Ince poised to follow him out with move to Everton or Monaco|newspaper=The Daily Telegraph |first=John |last=Percy |date=21 January 2014|accessdate=30 May 2016}}</ref><ref name=incegamble>{{cite news|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-2540662/Tom-Ince-set-Monaco-holding-talks-French-club-London.html|title=EXCLUSIVE: Ince set to gamble on Monaco move after talks with French club in London and dad Paul does not deny meeting|newspaper=Daily Mail |first=John |last=Edwards |date=16 January 2014|accessdate=30 May 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/vauxhall/tom-ince-transfer-monaco-move-3031412|title=Why a lucrative move to Monaco could be a great step for young English star Tom Ince|newspaper=Daily Mirror |first=John |last=Cross |date=20 January 2014|accessdate=30 May 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/25943926|title=Transfer window: Thomas Ince set for Hull & Sunderland talks|publisher=BBC Sport|date=29 January 2014|accessdate=30 May 2016}}</ref> However, Ince once again spurned Liverpool's advances, believing that he was not ready to move to a club of their size.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/sport/football/transfer-news/liverpool-transfer-news-tom-ince-3111430|title=New Crystal Palace signing Tom Ince rejected January move to Liverpool says father Paul|newspaper=Daily Mirror|date=4 February 2014|accessdate=3 November 2015}}</ref> European clubs [[AFC Ajax|Ajax]], [[Inter Milan]] and [[Paris Saint-Germain]] also revealed their interest<ref name=incegamble/><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/sport/football/transfer-news/ajax-want-blackpools-tom-ince-2928437|title=Ajax want to sign Blackpool starlet Tom Ince and could make a formal approach in January|newspaper=Daily Mirror |first=Alan |last=Nixon |date=15 December 2013|accessdate=30 May 2016}}</ref> and French club Monaco were reported to be leading the race to sign Ince on a free transfer in the Summer,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/teams/blackpool/10578339/Monaco-favourites-to-sign-Thomas-Ince-from-Blackpool.html|title=Monaco favourites to sign Thomas Ince from Blackpool|newspaper=The Daily Telegraph|date=16 January 2014|accessdate=30 May 2016}}</ref> with minimal compensation due to Blackpool if he did sign for a European club, around \u00a3155,000 compared to an expected \u00a34m if he signed for an English club.<ref name=incegamble/> Ince and his father met with representatives from Monaco in London on 16 January, just two days before Blackpool's 2\u20130 defeat to Barnsley, which was believed to be one of the reasons for Paul Ince being sacked as Blackpool manager.<ref name=incepoised/>\n\nHis father's departure was reported to be likely to accelerate Tom Ince's departure from Blackpool,<ref name=incepoised/> with a domestic loan deal considered most likely as it would allow him the freedom of choice in the Summer when his Blackpool contract had expired.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-2548665/Crystal-Palace-leading-race-sign-Blackpool-winger-Ince.html|title=Palace set to win race for Ince on loan \u2013 despite permanent bid from Stoke for Blackpool winger|newspaper=Daily Mail |first=Sami |last=Mokbel |date=30 January 2014|accessdate=30 May 2016}}</ref> A loan move to Crystal Palace, Stoke City, Swansea, Sunderland or Hull City was considered most likely, with the deal coming down to the size of the loan fee and what percentage of his wages was paid by the club loaning him out.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/sport/football/transfer-news/crystal-palace-sign-tom-ince-3094051|title=Crystal Palace sign Tom Ince on loan until the end of the season after paying Blackpool \u00a31million fee|newspaper=Daily Mirror |first=Alan |last=Nixon |date=30 January 2014|accessdate=30 May 2016}}</ref> On 30 January 2014, Ince signed for Premier League club Crystal Palace on loan for the remainder of the [[2013\u201314 Crystal Palace F.C. season|2013\u201314]] season for a loan fee of \u00a31&nbsp;million.<ref>{{cite news |last=Hytner |first=David |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2014/jan/31/crystal-palace-loan-deal-tom-ince |title=Crystal Palace move to secure \u00a31m loan deal for winger Tom Ince |newspaper=The Guardian |date=31 January 2014 |accessdate=29 May 2014}}</ref> Ince made his debut on 8 February 2014, playing 90 minutes and scoring the first of three goals for Crystal Palace on the day, in a 3\u20131 win against [[West Bromwich Albion F.C.|West Bromwich Albion]].\n\nInce started the next two matches, a 2\u20130 defeat to Manchester United on 22 February and a 0\u20130 draw with Swansea City on 2 March, then came off the bench in a 1\u20130 defeat to Southampton on 8 March. He started against Sunderland on 15 March, a match that also ended 0\u20130, and then did not make another appearance for over a month. He was an unused substitute for the next six Premier League matches, as manager [[Tony Pulis]] preferred to play [[Yannick Bolasie]] and [[Jason Puncheon]] on the wings. He came off the bench in a 2\u20130 defeat to Manchester City on 27 April and in a 3\u20133 draw against Liverpool on 5 May before starting the final game of the season, a 2\u20132 draw with Fulham on 11 May.\n\n===Hull City===\nWith his contract expiring at Blackpool and Ince unwilling to take up the option of a third year, clubs began to show an interest in signing him. Crystal Palace, [[Hull City A.F.C.|Hull City]], [[Newcastle United F.C.|Newcastle United]], [[Stoke City F.C.|Stoke City]], [[Sunderland A.F.C.|Sunderland]] and Swansea City from the Premier League and European clubs [[AS Monaco FC|Monaco]], [[Olympiacos F.C.|Olympiacos]] and Inter Milan all expressed a desire to sign him.<ref name=intercomingdays>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/27574677|title=Tom Ince: Inter Milan aim to complete deal 'in coming days'|publisher=BBC Sport|date=27 May 2014|accessdate=30 May 2016}}</ref><ref name=interreject>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2014/jun/06/tom-ince-rejects-inter-milan-blackpool|title=Tom Ince rejects chance to join Internazionale on free transfer|newspaper=The Guardian|date=6 June 2014|accessdate=3 November 2015}}</ref> Inter Milan, a club Ince's father had played for from 1995 to 1997, confirmed in May 2014 that they had offered Ince a contract<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dailystar.co.uk/sport/football/379339/Inter-Milan-confirm-contract-offer-to-ex-Liverpool-man-Tom-Ince|title=Inter Milan confirm contract offer to ex-Liverpool man Tom Ince|newspaper=Daily Star|date=17 May 2014|accessdate=3 November 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2014/may/26/tom-ince-inter-blackpool-transfer-father|title=Tom Ince relishing prospect of following in father's Inter footsteps|newspaper=The Guardian|date=26 May 2014|accessdate=3 November 2015}}</ref> and he spent several days in Monaco and then Milan discussing a move<ref name=intercomingdays/> but ultimately turned both Monaco and Inter Milan down.<ref name=interreject/> He said that \"after lengthy discussions with my family I have decided that my immediate future in the game lies in the Premier League\" although he \"still had ambitions to one day play in Europe\".<ref name=interreject/> In September 2015, he would go into more detail, saying that although there was \"nothing better\" than the lifestyle in Monaco, he \"felt the league itself and the question 'would I get lost over there?' especially being English, put me off a little.\" Likewise, although the history and memories from his father's time at Inter Milan were attractive, the club was in a transitional period \u2013 \"they weren't trying to challenge up at the top again, and it was a rebuilding process. Being a young lad, I didn't want any of that, I wanted to get in the Premier League.\"<ref name=snubsettling>{{cite news|url=http://www.skysports.com/football/news/12040/10005007/tom-ince-on-inter-and-monaco-snub-england-u21-drama-and-settling-at-derby|title=Tom Ince on Inter and Monaco snub, England U21 drama and settling at Derby|publisher=Sky Sports |first=Pete |last=Hall |date=25 September 2015|accessdate=30 May 2016}}</ref>\n\nAfter his contract expired at Blackpool, Ince transferred to Hull City on a free transfer in July 2014 and signed a two-year contract, with an agreement over compensation not initially made.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2014/jul/07/tom-ince-signs-hull-city |title=Tom Ince signs two-year contract with Hull City |date=7 July 2014 |accessdate=7 July 2014 |newspaper=The Guardian}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Hampson |first=Andy |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/transfers/tom-ince-to-hull-city-winger-moves-to-hull-city-after-inter-milan-deal-falls-through-9590370.html |title=Tom Ince to Hull City: Winger moves to Hull City after Inter Milan deal falls through |date=7 July 2014 |accessdate=7 July 2014 |newspaper=The Independent}}</ref> After much negotiation, and with a decision by an independent tribunal looming, Hull and Blackpool settled in January 2015 on a figure of \u00a31.6&nbsp;million, rising to \u00a32.3&nbsp;million, dependant on appearances and if Hull avoided relegation.<ref name=liverbank/><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/30835014|title=Tom Ince: Blackpool could get \u00a32.3m compensation from Hull|publisher=BBC Sport|date=21 January 2015|accessdate=3 November 2015}}</ref> Due to the earlier sell-on clause Liverpool had negotiated with Blackpool, Liverpool received \u00a3560,000.<ref name=liverbank/>\n\nInce came on as a substitute in both legs of Hull's Europa League third qualifying round tie against Slovakian club [[AS Tren\u010d\u00edn]] before making his league debut for the club on 16 August, playing 82 minutes of a 1\u20130 win away at Queens Park Rangers. He also came off the bench in both legs of the Europa League play-off round against Belgian side [[K.S.C. Lokeren Oost-Vlaanderen|Sporting Lokeren]]; sandwiched between those matches, he started in a 1\u20131 draw against Stoke City on 24 August. He started again for the club in a 2\u20131 defeat to Aston Villa on 31 August, though he was withdrawn after 57 minutes. He went a month before appearing again for the club, playing 90 minutes and scoring in a 3\u20132 defeat to West Bromwich Albion on 24 September. He later said that manager Steve Bruce's change in tactics, to a more defensive approach, left him sidelined.<ref name=snubsettling/>\n\nOn 30 October 2014, having played in only three of Hull's nine league matches of the season thus far, Ince signed on loan with Championship side [[Nottingham Forest F.C.|Nottingham Forest]] until 28 December.<ref>{{cite news|title=Tom Ince: Hull winger joins Nottingham Forest on loan|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/29830553|accessdate=30 October 2014|publisher=BBC Sport|date=30 October 2014}}</ref> He made his debut the following day, playing the full 90 minutes as Nottingham Forest lost 3\u20130 to Huddersfield Town. Of the next seven matches, Ince made three starts and two substitute appearances before being recalled early by his parent club.\n\nInce was recalled to Hull on 22 December 2014, along with [[Maynor Figueroa]] from [[Wigan Athletic F.C.|Wigan Athletic]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Hull City recall Tom Ince and Maynor Figueroa|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/30576846|accessdate=22 December 2014|publisher=BBC Sport|date=22 December 2014}}</ref> He went straight back into the team, coming on as a late substitute in Hull's 3\u20131 win at Sunderland on Boxing Day. He came off the bench two days later in a 1\u20130 defeat to Leicester and then started against Arsenal in the FA Cup on 4 January, a match Hull lost 2\u20130. He came on in the 39th minute of Hull's 1\u20130 defeat away to West Bromwich Albion on 10 January and then went three weeks before playing again, coming off the bench in a 3\u20130 defeat to Newcastle on 31 January. That was to be his final appearance for ''The Tigers''.\n\n===Derby County===\n[[File:Tom Ince 2017.jpg|thumb|upright|300px|Ince playing for [[Derby County F.C.|Derby County]] in 2017]]\n\nOn 2 February 2015, Ince joined [[EFL Championship|Championship]] club [[Derby County F.C.|Derby County]] on loan until the end of [[2014\u201315 Derby County F.C. season|the season]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Thomas Ince joins Derby from Hull City|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/31104738|accessdate=2 February 2015|publisher=BBC Sport|date=2 February 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | date = 3 July 2015| title= Tom Ince: Derby County sign Hull City winger for club record fee | url =http://soccernet.espn.go.com/news/story?id=537648&cc=5739 | publisher =BBC Football}}</ref> Derby manager [[Steve McClaren]] said that signing a player of Ince's calibre was a \"real coup\" and that he was confident Ince would make an impact for ''The Rams''.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/31104738|title=Transfer Deadline Day: Thomas Ince & Jesse Lingard join Derby|publisher=BBC Sport|date=2 February 2015|accessdate=4 June 2016}}</ref> Five days later, Ince scored twice on his debut for Derby in a 4\u20131 win against Bolton Wanderers: a \"superb\" free kick into the top-left corner of [[Andy Lonergan]]'s goal in the 39th minute and a \"thunderous\" shot from 12 yards in the 47th minute. He nearly bagged a hattrick, hitting the post in second-half stoppage time.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/31070588|title=Derby County 4\u20131 Bolton Wanderers|publisher=BBC Sport|date=7 February 2015|accessdate=4 June 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-2944039/Derby-County-4-1-Bolton-Wanderers-Tom-Ince-scores-league-goals-year-Rams-Championship.html|title=Derby County 4\u20131 Bolton Wanderers: Tom Ince scores first league goals for a year to keep Rams top of the Championship|newspaper=Daily Mail|date=7 February 2015|accessdate=4 June 2016}}</ref> Ince scored three more goals in his next two games: an emphatic finish in a 2\u20132 draw against Bournemouth on 10 February;<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/31105937|title=AFC Bournemouth 2\u20132 Derby County|publisher=BBC Sport|date=10 February 2015|accessdate=4 June 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2015/feb/10/bournemouth-derby-county-championship-match-report|title=Darren Bent equaliser for Derby costs Bournemouth Championship lead|newspaper=The Guardian|date=10 February 2015|accessdate=4 June 2016}}</ref> and another brace in a 3\u20133 draw away to Rotherham United on 17 February, a fine curling finish into the top-right corner after jinking past several players and turning in a [[Craig Forsyth]] cross at the near post.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/31423287|title=Rotherham United 3\u20133 Derby County|publisher=BBC Sport|date=17 February 2015|accessdate=4 June 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.skysports.com/football/rotherham-vs-derby/314137|title=Sky Bet Championship: Derby come from behind to draw 3\u20133 at Rotherham|publisher=Sky Sports|date=18 February 2015|accessdate=4 June 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2015/feb/17/rotherham-derby-championship-match-report|title=Darren Bent rescues point at Rotherham but Derby miss chance to go top|newspaper=The Guardian|date=17 February 2015|accessdate=4 June 2016}}</ref>\n\nAfter scoring five goals in three matches, Ince declared himself \"settled\" at Derby, saying that he had \"really found my feet and I'm feeling confident\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/31534173|title=Derby County: Tom Ince settled after five-goal start for Rams|publisher=BBC Sport|date=19 February 2015|accessdate=4 June 2016}}</ref> The next four games saw more good performances for Ince but no goals: he hit the post, had a free kick \"brilliantly\" saved by Sheffield Wednesday keeper [[Keiren Westwood]], narrowly curled an effort wide and won a penalty in a 3\u20132 win against Wednesday on 21 February;<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/31467127|title=Derby County 3\u20132 Sheffield Wednesday|publisher=BBC Sport|date=21 February 2015|accessdate=4 June 2016}}</ref> was a \"constant threat\" and placed a shot just wide in a 2\u20130 win against [[Charlton Athletic F.C.|Charlton Athletic]] on 24 February;<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-2967568/Derby-County-2-0-Charlton-Athletic-Jeff-Hendrick-stars-Championship-leaders-cruise-past-Charlton.html|title=Derby County 2\u20130 Charlton Athletic: Jeff Hendrick stars for Championship leaders as they cruise past the Addicks|newspaper=Daily Mail|date=24 February 2015|accessdate=4 June 2016}}</ref> was twice denied by deflections late in the second half of a 2\u20130 defeat to [[Fulham F.C.|Fulham]] on 28 February;<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/football-league/fulham-vs-derby-county-match-report-leaders-slip-up-as-returning-scott-parker-rallies-home-side-10077614.html|title=Fulham vs Derby County match report: Leaders slip up as returning Scott Parker rallies home side|newspaper=The Independent|date=28 February 2015|accessdate=4 June 2016}}</ref> and missed several chances in a 2\u20130 defeat to [[Brighton & Hove Albion F.C.|Brighton & Hove Albion]] on 3 March that saw Derby register 19 attempts at goal.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-2978211/Brighton-2-0-Derby-County-Super-subs-Dale-Stephens-Kazenga-Lua-Lua-seal-stunning-Seagulls-win-promotion-chasing-Rams.html|title=Brighton 2\u20130 Derby County: Super subs Dale Stephens and Kazenga LuaLua knock Rams off top spot|newspaper=Daily Mail|date=3 March 2015|accessdate=4 June 2016}}</ref> Ince put Derby 2\u20130 up against [[Birmingham City F.C.|Birmingham City]] on 7 March, slipping through two defenders and shooting low under Birmingham keeper [[Darren Randolph]], though two late goals for ''The Blues'' saw them rescue a point, with the first coming from the penalty spot after Ince hauled down [[Robert Tesche]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-2984089/Derby-2-2-Birmingham-Paul-Caddis-Clayton-Donaldson-injury-time-strikes-salvage-dramatic-draw-against-Rams.html|title=Derby 2\u20132 Birmingham: Paul Caddis and Clayton Donaldson injury-time strikes salvage dramatic draw against the Rams|newspaper=Daily Mail|date=7 March 2015|accessdate=4 June 2016}}</ref> He only scored once in his next six games, this in a 2\u20132 draw at home to Watford on 3 April, before scoring four goals in his next three. The first was the second goal in a 4\u20130 rout of Blackpool on 14 April, a brace followed in a 4\u20134 draw against Huddersfield Town on 18 April and the last came in a 3\u20133 draw against Millwall on 25 April. He thus finished his spell at Derby with 11 goals in 18 matches. Of the 8 matches in which he scored, 6 of them finished in draws.\n\nOn 3 July 2015, Derby County signed Ince on a four-year contract for \u00a34.75&nbsp;million,<ref>{{cite news|title=Thomas Ince joins Derby from Hull City|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/33382692|publisher=BBC Sport|date=2 February 2015|accessdate=3 July 2015}}</ref> with Ince briefly becoming the club's most-expensive signing. His record was surpassed less than one month later as the club bought midfielder [[Bradley Johnson]] from [[Norwich City F.C.|Norwich City]] for \u00a36&nbsp;million.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.derbytelegraph.co.uk/Derby-County-Rams-sign-Bradley-Johnson-Norwich/story-27716877-detail/story.html|title=Derby County: Rams sign Bradley Johnson from Norwich City in club record deal|newspaper=Derby Telegraph|date=1 September 2015|accessdate=3 November 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150909001550/http://www.derbytelegraph.co.uk/Derby-County-Rams-sign-Bradley-Johnson-Norwich/story-27716877-detail/story.html|archive-date=9 September 2015|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The sale of Ince was reported to have left Hull manager [[Steve Bruce]] livid, with Bruce saying that he \"wouldn't have sold Tom and I did all I could to keep him... we shouldn't be selling our top young players when trying to put together a team to challenge for an immediate return to the Premier League. I saw Tom as an integral part of my plans. But Derby met the buy-out clause and then it was the choice of others [at Hull] to let him leave.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-3149264/Tom-Ince-4-75m-sale-Derby-County-leaves-Hull-manager-Steve-Bruce-livid.html|title=Tom Ince \u00a34.75m sale to Derby County leaves Hull manager Steve Bruce livid|newspaper=Daily Mail|date=4 July 2015|accessdate=3 November 2015}}</ref> Ince started all of Derby's first eight league matches, also coming on as a substitute in the club's 2\u20131 League Cup defeat to Portsmouth on 12 August. His first goal arrived on 15 September, the only goal against Reading at the [[Madejski Stadium]]. He missed the next match, a 0\u20130 draw at home to Burnley on 21 September, with a minor training ground injury.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.burtonmail.co.uk/Derby-County-wait-Tom-Ince-s-fitness-ahead-trip/story-27847096-detail/story.html|title=Derby County wait on Tom Ince's fitness ahead of trip to MK Dons|newspaper=Burton Mail|date=23 September 2015|accessdate=3 November 2015}}{{Dead link|date=September 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> On his return to the starting XI away to newly promoted Milton Keynes Dons on 26 September, Ince provided a 90th minute assist for [[Darren Bent]] and scored in the 96th minute to seal a 3\u20131 win for ''The Rams''.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/34299081|title=MK Dons 1\u20133 Derby|publisher=BBC Sport|date=26 September 2015|accessdate=3 November 2015}}</ref> Ince made it three goals in three games on 3 October, grabbing the second in a 2\u20130 win against Brentford. He started the next three League matches, against Wolves on 18 October, Blackburn Rovers on 21 October and against Huddersfield Town on 24 October but was taken off in the 26th minute of the latter match. He had injured his ankle but it was not as bad as first feared<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.derbytelegraph.co.uk/Derby-County-Tom-Ince-doubt-Saturday-Rotherham/story-28062825-detail/story.html|title=Derby County: Tom Ince a doubt for Saturday against Rotherham|newspaper=Derby Telegraph|date=27 October 2015|accessdate=3 November 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151030002321/http://www.derbytelegraph.co.uk/Derby-County-Tom-Ince-doubt-Saturday-Rotherham/story-28062825-detail/story.html|archive-date=30 October 2015|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> and although he missed the next two League matches against Rotherham United and QPR, he returned to the team for the East Midlands derby against his former club Nottingham Forest on 6 November.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.derbytelegraph.co.uk/Derby-County-Tom-Ince-QPR-game-fit-face/story-28099220-detail/story.html|title=Derby County: Tom Ince out of QPR game but could be fit to face Nottingham Forest|newspaper=Derby Telegraph|date=2 November 2015|accessdate=3 November 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151104032800/http://www.derbytelegraph.co.uk/Derby-County-Tom-Ince-QPR-game-fit-face/story-28099220-detail/story.html|archive-date=4 November 2015|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nOn 15 December, Ince scored his first professional hat-trick in a 4\u20130 win against Bristol City. The first was a low finish past City keeper [[Frank Fielding]] in the 42nd minute after a mazy run through three defenders; then he intercepted the ball inside his own half and ran through on goal before firing a shot under Fielding in the 63rd minute; his third in the 71st minute was drilled into the bottom corner after a combination with Darren Bent.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.derbytelegraph.co.uk/VIDEO-Derby-County-4-Bristol-City-0-highlights/story-28378228-detail/story.html|title=VIDEO: Derby County 4, Bristol City 0, the highlights|newspaper=Derby Telegraph|date=16 December 2015|accessdate=30 May 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151219034155/http://www.derbytelegraph.co.uk/VIDEO-Derby-County-4-Bristol-City-0-highlights/story-28378228-detail/story.html|archive-date=19 December 2015|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-3361606/Derby-4-0-Bristol-City-Tom-Ince-scores-hat-trick-against-struggling-Robins-Derby-Championship.html|title=Derby 4\u20130 Bristol City: Tom Ince scores first ever hat-trick against struggling Robins to move Derby up to third in the Championship|newspaper=Daily Mail|date=15 December 2015|accessdate=30 May 2016}}</ref> The result moved Derby up to third in the table and manager [[Paul Clement (football manager)|Paul Clement]] praised Ince, saying that \"he's been a little bit inconsistent by his standards so far this season so it was a very good performance from him and will be brilliant for his confidence.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/35035926|title=Derby County 4\u20130 Bristol City|publisher=BBC Sport|date=15 December 2015|accessdate=30 May 2016}}</ref> Ince scored again in the next match, the only goal in a 1\u20130 win at home to Ipswich Town on 19 December. His man-of-the-match performance also saw him provide three good chances, for teammates Bradley Johnson, [[Chris Martin (footballer, born 1988)|Chris Martin]] and [[Johnny Russell (footballer)|Johnny Russell]], as well as have a 25-yard free-kick saved by Ipswich goalie [[Dean Gerken]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-3367157/Ipswich-0-1-Derby-Tom-Ince-grabs-half-winner-continue-fine-goalscoring-form.html|title=Ipswich 0\u20131 Derby: Tom Ince grabs first-half winner to continue his fine goalscoring form|newspaper=Daily Mail|date=19 December 2015|accessdate=30 May 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.derbytelegraph.co.uk/LIVE-Ipswich-Town-0-1-Derby-County-Tom-Ince/story-28394644-detail/story.html|title=LIVE: Ipswich Town 0\u20131 Derby County \u2013 Tom Ince strikes again for Rams|newspaper=Derby Telegraph|date=19 December 2015|accessdate=30 May 2016}}{{Dead link|date=September 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> He missed two good opportunities in the next match, a 2\u20130 win over Fulham on [[Boxing Day]],<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/35139097|title=Derby County 2\u20130 Fulham|publisher=BBC Sport|date=26 December 2015|accessdate=30 May 2016}}</ref> but atoned against fierce rivals Leeds United on 29 December. He came on in the 76th minute with Derby 2\u20131 down, scoring a \"brilliant\" equaliser just two minutes later, drilling a \"fine finish\" into the bottom corner.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.skysports.com/football/leeds-vs-derby/339814|title=Leeds 2\u20132 Derby: Tom Ince rescues Derby point in thriller|publisher=Sky Sports|date=29 December 2015|accessdate=30 May 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-3377893/Leeds-vs-Derby-updates-Championship-games-LIVE-latest-Massimo-Cellino-lets-Sky-cameras-in.html|title=Leeds 2\u20132 Derby RESULT: Tom Ince nets late equaliser after hosts' Sky Sports row... plus updates from across the Championship|newspaper=Daily Mail|date=29 December 2015|accessdate=30 May 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/teams/leeds-united/12073697/Leeds-United-2-Derby-Couny-2-match-report-Tom-Ince-rescues-point-for-Derby-to-keep-promotion-hopes-on-track.html|title=Leeds United 2 Derby County 2, match report: Tom Ince rescues point for Derby to keep promotion hopes on track|newspaper=The Daily Telegraph|date=29 December 2015|accessdate=30 May 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2015/dec/29/leeds-united-derby-county-championship-match-report|title=Tom Ince grabs Derby County a point in thrilling draw with Leeds|newspaper=The Guardian|date=29 December 2015|accessdate=30 May 2016}}</ref>\n\nInce then endured a difficult spell, not scoring in his next twelve league and cup appearances. After the first seven appearances, during which Derby lost five times, drew twice, only scored three goals and sacked manager Paul Clement, he lost his place in the starting line-up. This coincided with a return to form for the team, who won two of their next three matches, with Ince making second-half substitute appearances. He was restored to the starting eleven on 5 March for a 2\u20130 win against Huddersfield Town and ended his barren spell two matches later on 12 March, scoring a brace either side of a Chris Martin goal to give ''The Rams'' a 3\u20130 lead against Rotherham United. However, three late Rotherham goals saw the away side rescue a point. Ince rounded out the season with two more goals: the second in a 4\u20131 thrashing of Bolton Wanderers on 9 April and the 57th-minute winner in a 3\u20132 victory at Bristol City on 19 April. Derby finished the season in fifth place and played fourth-placed Hull City in the [[2016 Football League play-offs#Championship|play-off semi-finals]], losing 3\u20130 at home and winning 2\u20130 away to go out 3\u20132 on aggregate to the eventual [[2016 Football League Championship play-off Final|play-off Final]] winners. Ince did not score his first goal of the 2016\u201317 season until 27 September, the first in a 2\u20130 win at Cardiff City. In November, he scored four goals in back-to-back games: braces each in a 3\u20132 win at Wolves on 5 November and in a 3\u20130 win over Rotherham on 19 November. Ince ended the [[2016\u201317 Derby County F.C. season|2016\u201317]] season as top scorer with 15 goals as the Rams finished in 9th position.<ref>{{cite web |title=Rotherham 1-1 Derby |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/39760412 |website=BBC Sport |accessdate=21 August 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Huddersfield Town===\nOn 4 July 2017, Ince signed for newly promoted Premier League club [[Huddersfield Town A.F.C.|Huddersfield Town]] on an initial three-year contract for an undisclosed fee.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/40456223|title=Huddersfield sign Tom Ince & Danny Williams, Kasey Palmer joins on loan|publisher=BBC Sport|date=4 July 2017|accessdate=11 July 2017}}</ref> He scored his first goal with the club in the Premier League on 26 December during a 1\u20131 draw with Stoke City.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/premier-league/huddersfield-1-stoke-city-1-tom-ince-first-goal-four-years-point-terriers-a8129136.html|title=Tom Ince nets first goal in four years but Huddersfield denied by Stoke|date=26 December 2017|newspaper=The Independent|access-date=27 December 2017}}</ref> Ince played 37 times in [[2017\u201318 Huddersfield Town A.F.C. season|2017\u201318 season]] helping the Terriers avoid relegation, finishing in 16th position.<ref>{{cite web |title=Value of Ince deal 'made sense' for Huddersfield Town, insists Wagner |url=https://www.yorkshirepost.co.uk/sport/football/huddersfield-town/value-of-ince-deal-made-sense-for-huddersfield-town-insists-wagner-1-9268122 |website=Yorkshire Post |accessdate=21 August 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Stoke City===\nInce signed for newly relegated Championship club Stoke City on 24 July 2018 on a four-year contract for an initial fee of \u00a310&nbsp;million, which could rise to \u00a312&nbsp;million with add-ons.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/44938650 |title=Tom Ince: Stoke City sign Huddersfield winger for initial \u00a310m fee |publisher=BBC Sport |date=24 July 2018 |accessdate=24 July 2018}}</ref> He made his Stoke debut on 5 August 2018 against [[Leeds United F.C.|Leeds United]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Leeds 3-1 Stoke |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/44995752 |website=BBC Sport |accessdate=21 August 2018}}</ref> Ince played 41 times for Stoke in [[2018\u201319 Stoke City F.C. season|2018\u201319]], scoring six goals as the Potters finished in a mid-table position of 16th.<ref name=sb1819/>\n\n==International career==\n[[File:Tom Ince (cropped).jpg|thumb|upright|Ince playing for [[England national under-21 football team|England U21]] in 2012]]\n\nInce made four appearances for [[England national under-17 football team|England Under-17s]] in 2009 and another four for the [[England national under-19 football team|Under 19s]] in 2011. On 29 August 2012 he was called up to the [[England national under-21 football team|Under 21 squad]] by manager [[Stuart Pearce]] for the [[2013 UEFA European Under-21 Football Championship qualification Group 8|European Championship qualifying]] games against [[Azerbaijan national under-21 football team|Azerbaijan]] on 1 September and [[Norway national under-21 football team|Norway]] four days later.<ref name=gazette4876120>{{cite news|last=Watt|first=William|title=Ince handed England call-up|url=http://www.blackpoolgazette.co.uk/sport/football/blackpool-fc/ince-handed-england-call-up-1-4876120|newspaper=Blackpool Gazette|accessdate=29 August 2012|date=29 August 2012}}</ref> He made his under-21 debut in the 2\u20130 win over Azerbaijan at [[Dalga Arena]], [[Baku]].<ref name=uefa2006943>{{cite web|title=Azerbaijan 0\u20132 England|url=http://www.uefa.com/under21/season=2013/matches/round=2000192/match=2006943/index.html|publisher=UEFA|accessdate=6 September 2012|date=6 September 2012}}</ref>\n\nOn 5 February 2013, he scored his first goals for the under-21 side, scoring twice in a 4\u20130 win against [[Sweden national under-21 football team|Sweden]] in [[Walsall]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thefa.com/England/mens-under-21s/News/2013/england-u21s-v-sweden-latest |title=England 4\u20130 Sweden|publisher= The Football Association|date= 5 February 2013|accessdate=5 February 2013}}</ref> In March 2015, he ruled himself out of selection for future under-21 squads.<ref>{{cite news|title=Tom Ince: Gareth Southgate reveals winger's Under-21s snub|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/0/football/31970541|accessdate=20 March 2015|publisher=BBC Sport|date=19 March 2015}}</ref> This caused a great deal of controversy, which shocked Ince.<ref name=snubsettling/>\n\n{{quote|\"Bear in mind I had been playing for the U21s for the past three years, had 20\u201325 caps, played in [[2013 UEFA European Under-21 Championship|the [2013] European Championship]] under Stuart Pearce. I was 23, and the oldest one there by a good 18 months. I felt at the time I hadn't really played a lot of club football, and I'd been getting banded from pillar to post, and needed a summer off to settle down, and plan my next move. The next move was a vital one... it is time to be kicking on. I went to Croatia in [[2015 UEFA European Under-21 Championship qualification play-offs|the play-offs]] to qualify [for the [[2015 UEFA European Under-21 Championship|2015 under-21 championships]]], and I was on the bench. I made the decision and it was time to move on. Like everything in life, in any job, you get that feeling the time is right to move on.\" \u2013 Ince on his decision to rule himself out of consideration for the England under-21s.<ref name=snubsettling/>}}\n\n==Style of play==\nInce is left-footed and began his career as a [[Midfielder#Winger|left winger]].<ref name=blacksign/> However, when he joined Blackpool, he was often deployed on the right, either as a winger or an [[inside forward]], cutting in on his favoured left foot. He has also played more centrally as an [[Midfielder#Attacking midfielder|attacking midfielder]] or [[Forward (association football)|forward]].<ref name=lpoolclosein/> Ince's main attributes are his pace, acceleration and skill on the ball.<ref name=lpoolclosein/> He has said that he enjoys \"exciting people, scoring goals, creating goals\" and is \"not one of those old fashioned wingers who just gets crosses in, I like to create things, show bits of magic.\"<ref name=snubsettling/>\n\n==Career statistics==\n{{updated|match played 7 March 2020}}\n\n{| class=wikitable style=text-align:center\n|+ Appearances and goals by club, season and competition\n|-\n!rowspan=2|Club\n!rowspan=2|Season\n!colspan=3|League\n!colspan=2|[[FA Cup]]\n!colspan=2|[[EFL Cup|League Cup]]\n!colspan=2|Other\n!colspan=2|Total\n|-\n!Division!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals\n|-\n|[[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]]\n|[[2010\u201311 Liverpool F.C. season|2010\u201311]]<ref name=sb1011>{{soccerbase season|55425|2010|accessdate=13 October 2017}}</ref>\n|[[Premier League]]\n|0||0||colspan=2|\u2014||1||0||0||0||1||0\n|-\n|[[Notts County F.C.|Notts County]] (loan)\n|[[2010\u201311 Notts County F.C. season|2010\u201311]]<ref name=sb1011/>\n