onours==\n'''Individual'''\n*[[PFA Team of the Year]]: [[PFA Team of the Year (2010s)#Championship 4|2012\u201313 Championship]]<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/22331030 |title=Gareth Bale wins PFA Player of Year and Young Player awards |publisher=BBC Sport |date=28 April 2013 |accessdate=23 May 2018}}</ref>\n*[[Football League Awards#2013 Awards|Football League Young Player of the Year]]: 2012\u201313\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n*{{Soccerbase}}\n\n{{Stoke City F.C. squad}}\n{{Navboxes\n| title = Awards\n| bg = gold\n| fg = navy\n| list1 = \n{{Blackpool F.C. Player of the Year}}\n{{2012\u201313 Football League Championship PFA Team of the Year}}\n{{The Football League Young Player of the Year}}\n}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ince, Tom}}\n[[Category:1992 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:English people of Barbadian descent]]\n[[Category:English people of Trinidad and Tobago descent]]\n[[Category:Black English sportspeople]]\n[[Category:Footballers from Stockport]]\n[[Category:English footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football wingers]]\n[[Category:Liverpool F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Notts County F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Blackpool F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Crystal Palace F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Hull City A.F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Nottingham Forest F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Derby County F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Huddersfield Town A.F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Stoke City F.C. players]]\n[[Category:English Football League players]]\n[[Category:Premier League players]]\n[[Category:England youth international footballers]]\n[[Category:England under-21 international footballers]]\n", "name_user": "86.2.253.125", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tom_Ince"}
{"title_page": "Hakea erinacea", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2019}}\n{{speciesbox\n|name = Hedgehog hakea\n|image = Hakea_erinacea-Hedge-hog_Hakea.JPG\n|image_caption = ''Hakea erinacea'' at [[John Forrest National Park]], Western Australia\n|genus = Hakea\n|species = erinacea\n|authority = [[Carl Meissner|Meisn.]]<ref name=\"APC\">{{cite web |title=''Hakea erinacea'' |url=https://biodiversity.org.au/nsl/services/search?product=APC&tree.id=51209179&name=Hakea+erinacea&inc._scientific=&inc.scientific=on&inc._cultivar=&max=100&display=apc&search=true |website=APC |publisher=Council of Heads of Australasian Herbaria |accessdate=24 March 2019}}</ref>\n|range_map = Hakea erinaceaDistMap47.png\n|range_map_caption = Occurrence data from [[Australasian Virtual Herbarium|AVH]]\n|}}\n\n'''''Hakea erinacea''''', commonly known as  '''hedgehog<ref name=\"FLORABASE\">{{cite web |title=''Hakea erinacea'' |url=https://florabase.dpaw.wa.gov.au/browse/profile/2158 |website=FloraBase Online |publisher=Western Australian Government |accessdate=24 March 2019}}</ref> or porcupine hakea''',<ref name=\"DAVE\">{{cite web |title=''Hakea erinacea'' |url=https://davesgarden.com/guides/pf/showimage/432714.html#b |website=Daves Garden |accessdate=24 March 2019}}</ref> is a shrub in the family [[Proteaceae]] endemic to [[Southwest Australia|south-west]] [[Western Australia]].\n\n==Description==\n''Hakea erinacea'' is erect in habit, with spiny short [[terete]]  leaves, and grows to over 1.5 metres in height and about the same width. The flowers are cream to white in colour with red to purple pistils and are produced between May and November.<ref name=\"florabase\">{{FloraBase | name = ''Hakea erinacea'' Meisn. | id = 2158}}</ref> The small smooth fruit are narrow, curved and end in a short pointed beak. Many Hakea retain their fruit, however this species sheds its seed when ripe.<ref name=\"PCA\">{{cite book |last1=Young |first1=J A |title=Hakeas of Western Australia:A Field and Identification Guide |publisher=J A Young |isbn=0-9585778-2-X}}</ref>\n\n==Taxonomy and naming==\n''Hakea erinacea'' was first described in 1845 by [[Carl Meisner]] and the description was published in ''Proteaceae. Plantae Preissianae''.<ref name=\"BHL\">{{cite web |title=Proteaceae. Plantae Preissianae |url=https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/item/9227#page/564/mode/1up |website=Biodiversity Heritage Library |accessdate=9 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"APNI\">{{cite web |title=''Hakea erinacea'' |url=https://biodiversity.org.au/nsl/services/rest/instance/apni/480114 |website=Australian Plant Name Index |accessdate=9 April 2020}}</ref>  It derives its name from the Latin ''erinaceus''-a hedgehog, referring to its very spiky leaves.<ref name=\"florabase\"/> \n\n==Distribution and habitat==\n''Hakea erinacea'' grows on sandy loam, clay and lateritic gravel on the coastal plains and the [[Darling Ranges]] north of Perth.<ref name=\"PCA\"/>\n\n==Conservation status==\n''H. erinacea'' is presently listed by Western Australian government as \"not threatened\".<ref name=\"florabase\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q5640387}}\n\n[[Category:Hakea|erinacea]]\n[[Category:Eudicots of Western Australia]]\n[[Category:Plants described in 1845]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2019}}\n{{speciesbox\n|name = Hedgehog hakea\n|image = Hakea_erinacea-Hedge-hog_Hakea.JPG\n|image_caption = ''Hakea erinacea'' at [[John Forrest National Park]], Western Australia\n|genus = Hakea\n|species = erinacea\n|authority = [[Carl Meissner|Meisn.]]<ref name=\"APC\">{{cite web |title=''Hakea erinacea'' |url=https://biodiversity.org.au/nsl/services/search?product=APC&tree.id=51209179&name=Hakea+erinacea&inc._scientific=&inc.scientific=on&inc._cultivar=&max=100&display=apc&search=true |website=APC |publisher=Council of Heads of Australasian Herbaria |accessdate=24 March 2019}}</ref>\n|range_map = Hakea erinaceaDistMap47.png\n|range_map_caption = Occurrence data from [[Australasian Virtual Herbarium|AVH]]\n|}}\n\n'''''Hakea erinacea''''', commonly known as  '''hedgehog<ref name=\"FLORABASE\">{{cite web |title=''Hakea erinacea'' |url=https://florabase.dpaw.wa.gov.au/browse/profile/2158 |website=FloraBase Online |publisher=Western Australian Government |accessdate=24 March 2019}}</ref> or porcupine hakea''',<ref name=\"DAVE\">{{cite web |title=''Hakea erinacea'' |url=https://davesgarden.com/guides/pf/showimage/432714.html#b |website=Daves Garden |accessdate=24 March 2019}}</ref> is a shrub in the family [[Proteaceae]] endemic to [[Southwest Australia|south-west]] [[Western Australia]].\n\n==Description==\n''Hakea erinacea'' is erect in habit, with spiny short [[terete]]  leaves, and grows to over 1.5 metres in height and about the same width. The flowers are cream to white in colour with red to purple pistils and are produced between May and November.<ref name=\"florabase\">{{FloraBase | name = ''Hakea erinacea'' Meisn. | id = 2158}}</ref> The small smooth fruit are narrow, curved and end in a short pointed beak. Many Hakea retain their fruit, however this species sheds its seed when ripe.<ref name=\"PCA\">{{cite book |last1=Young |first1=J A |title=Hakeas of Western Australia:A Field and Identification Guide |publisher=J A Young |isbn=0-9585778-2-X}}</ref>\n==Taxonomy and naming==\n''Hakea erinacea'' was first described in 1845 by [[Carl Meisner]].  It derives its name from the Latin ''erinaceus''-a hedgehog, referring to its very spiky leaves.<ref name=\"florabase\"/> \n==Distribution and habitat==\n''Hakea erinacea'' grows on sandy loam, clay and lateritic gravel on the coastal plains and the [[Darling Ranges]] north of Perth.<ref name=\"PCA\"/>\n==Conservation status==\n''H. erinacea'' is presently listed by Western Australian government as \"not threatened\".<ref name=\"florabase\"/>\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q5640387}}\n\n[[Category:Hakea|erinacea]]\n[[Category:Eudicots of Western Australia]]\n[[Category:Plants described in 1845]]\n", "name_user": "Allthingsnative", "label": "safe", "comment": "Expand T & N, add references", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hakea_erinacea"}
{"title_page": "Xandria", "text_new": "{{About|the German metal band}}\n\n{{Infobox musical artist <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject_Musicians -->\n| name                = Xandria\n| image               = Xandria-metalfest-pilsen-2014-06-01.jpg\n| caption             = Xandria at [[Metalfest]] in [[Plze\u0148|Pilsen]], [[Czech Republic]] (2014)\n| image_size          = 300\n| landscape           = Yes\n| background          = group_or_band\n| alias               = \n| origin              = [[Bielefeld]], [[Germany]]\n| genre               = {{flatlist|\n*[[Symphonic metal]]\n*[[Power metal|power metal]]\n}}\n| years_active        = 1994\u20131997, 1999\u2013present\n| label               = [[Drakkar Entertainment]] (2003\u20132011)<br>[[Napalm Records|Napalm]] (2011\u2013present)\n| associated_acts     = \n| website             = {{URL|http://www.xandria.de}}\n| current_members     = Marco Heubaum<br />Gerit Lamm<br />Philip Restemeier<br/>Steven Wussow<!--- Do not add Aeva Maurelle as a current member, as she has not been announced as Xandria's official vocalist. --->\n| past_members        = [[#Former members|See below]]\n}}\n\n'''Xandria''' is a [[Germany|German]] [[symphonic metal]] band, founded by Marco Heubaum in 1994.\n\n==History==\nXandria was started as a project band in 1994 in [[Bielefeld]], Germany by Marco Heubaum, the band's main composer and at the time vocalist, and a friend to play drums, but disbanded in 1997 after recording one demo.\n\nThe band was restarted with a different line-up in 1999. Marco stepped down from the role of vocalist and was joined by local musician Roland Krueger on bass. In 2000, they recorded one demo that was released on the internet and after its release, current drummer Gerit Lamm joined the band. The female vocalist that recorded the demo left the band to follow other plans and was replaced by [[Lisa Middelhauve|Lisa Schaphaus]]. At the same time, writing of the debut album started.\n\nIn 2002, the band signed to [[Drakkar Records]] and was joined by current lead guitarist Philip Restemeier. As work on the debut album progressed, the band started playing shows in and around Bielefeld. In the winter of 2002, the band entered the studio to record their debut album ''[[Kill the Sun]]''. They released ''Kill the Sun'' in May 2003, and it reached No. 98 on the German music charts.<ref name=ML>{{cite web |url=http://www.musicline.de/de/chartverfolgung_summary/artist/Xandria/?type=longplay |title=Xandria \u2014 Longplay-Chartverfolgung |language=German |work=musicline.de |publisher=Phononet GmbH |accessdate=5 June 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121010132340/http://www.musicline.de/de/chartverfolgung_summary/artist/Xandria/?type=longplay |archive-date=10 October 2012 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> To promote the album, the band played a few shows with [[Schandmaul]] and [[Subway to Sally]]. Then they went on a three-week tour of Germany with [[Tanzwut]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://xandria.de/?page_id=47|title=Biography|work=Xandria|accessdate=25 November 2014}}</ref>\n\nAfter playing some festivals in support of ''[[Kill the Sun]]'', the band started writing their second album. Recording of the album began in December 2003 at Pleasure Park Studios, with producer Jos\u00e9 Alvarez-Brill. Production on the album was finished in February 2004. Shortly after the recordings were completed, bassist Roland Krueger left the band and was replaced by Nils Middelhauve. ''[[Ravenheart]]'' was released on May 24, 2004, and it stayed on the charts for seven weeks, reaching No. 36.<ref name=ML/>\n\nIn 2005 they released their third album, ''[[India (Xandria album)|India]]'', which reached No. 30 on the German charts.<ref name=ML/> Xandria began recording their fourth album, ''[[Salom\u00e9 \u2013 The Seventh Veil]]'', on December 14, 2006. It was released on May 25, 2007 and reached No. 41 on the German charts.<ref name=ML/>\n\n[[Lisa Middelhauve]] (n\u00e9e Schaphaus) resigned on April 30, 2008 citing personal reasons and discomfort in being the band's [[frontwoman]]. The band found a new singer in February 2009, Kerstin Bischof a.k.a. Lakonia, best known for her collaborations with the band [[Axxis]]. However, after just one year Kerstin Bischof decided to leave the band to concentrate on a different career, and [[Lisa Middelhauve|Middelhauve]] replaced her for a series of concerts in Summer 2010.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=135376 |title=Xandria once again looking for lead singer |date=18 February 2010 |work=[[Blabbermouth]] |accessdate=18 February 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110606063855/http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=135376 |archivedate=6 June 2011 }}</ref> On December 19, 2010, Xandria announced the addition of 29-year-old female singer [[Manuela Kraller]] to the group's ranks. Manuela Kraller made her live debut at the \"Classic Meets Pop\" event on January 7, 2011 at the Seidensticker Halle in Bielefeld, Germany.<ref>[http://www.roadrunnerreords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=151171]{{dead link|date=July 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nOn February 24, 2012, ''[[Neverworld's End]]'' was released. It was the only album [[Manuela Kraller]] had made with the band.\n\nOn February 5, 2013, the band announced on their website and Facebook page their new bass player Steven Wussow, along with the message that they would have entered the studio again for their next studio album the same year.\n\nAs of October 25, 2013, the band announced on their website that Kraller had left the band to pursue a different career and announced Dutch [[Ex Libris (band)|Ex Libris]] singer [[Dianne van Giersbergen]] as their new vocalist. ''[[Sacrificium (Xandria album)|Sacrificium]]'' was released in the following year. The year after, the band released their first EP titled ''[[Fire & Ashes (EP)|Fire & Ashes]]'' on July 31, 2015.\n\nTheir seventh album, ''[[Theater of Dimensions]]'' was released on January 27, 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/xandria-to-release-theater-of-dimensions-album-in-january/|title=XANDRIA To Release 'Theater Of Dimensions' Album In January|work=[[Blabbermouth.net]]|accessdate=September 22, 2016|date=September 22, 2016}}</ref> Following the release of the album, Xandria embarked on a few shows in Europe including their first headlining tour in North America with [[Kobra and the Lotus]] and [[Once Human]] in May 2017.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/xandria-to-tour-north-america-with-kobra-and-the-lotus-once-human/ |title=Xandria to Tour North America with Kobra and the Lotus & Once Human |date=March 17, 2017 |work=Blabbermouth.net |accessdate=March 17, 2017 }}</ref> Due to personal reasons, Xandria had cancelled their upcoming second half of the US tour as well as the Russian tour. Aeva Maurelle from the band ''Aeverium'' was the temporary vocalist for the European dates in the fall.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/xandria-cancels-u-s-tour-announces-stand-in-singer-for-european-shows/ |title=XANDRIA Cancels U.S. Tour, Announces Stand-In Singer For European shows |work=Blabbermouth |date=September 12, 2017 |accessdate=September 12, 2017 }}</ref>\n\nOn September 13, 2017, Dianne posted on her Facebook page that she had left Xandria. This due to having received pressure to perform from Xandria's management and the band while being physically unable to, giving her stress confirmed by doctors.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://bravewords.com/news/vocalist-dianne-van-giersbergen-i-am-leaving-xandria-emotional-audio-message-streaming |title=Vocalist DIANNE VAN GIERSBERGEN - \"I Am Leaving XANDRIA\"; Emotional Audio Message Streaming |magazine=BraveWords |date=September 13, 2017 |accessdate=September 13, 2017 }}</ref> Two days later on September 15, 2017, ex-vocalist Manuela Kraller shared a message to the public on her Facebook page, revealing that her reason to leave four years earlier was exactly the same one. She praised Dianne for having the courage to be open about the situation to the public, which she didn't dare to at the time, but now finally did.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/manuela.kraller/posts/10214661543759254 |title=Manuela Kraller - Shocked about the news, that Dianne left... |publisher=Facebook |date=September 14, 2017 |accessdate=September 15, 2017 }}</ref> Ex-vocalist Lisa Middelhauve also released a statement about Dianne's departure on the same day. She herein did not only speak about herself but also about ex-bassplayer Nils Middelhauve, whom she was married to at the time he was in the band but is now divorced from. It can be concluded that he too left Xandria under negative circumstances.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/48294212372/photos/a.437215032372.238222.48294212372/10154686766497373/?type=3 |title=Aaaand here we go. The statement. Of... - Lisa Middelhauve |publisher=Facebook |date=September 15, 2017 |accessdate=September 15, 2017 }}</ref> Guitarist Phillip Restemeier spoke about the reason behind Dianne's departure in an interview during the European tour.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/xandria-guitarist-explains-singer-dianne-van-giersbergens-departure-video/|title=XANDRIA Guitarist Explains Singer DIANNE VAN GIERSBERGEN's Departure (Video)|work=Blabbermouth|date=November 26, 2017|accessdate=November 28, 2017}}</ref>\n\nSteven Wussow was confirmed to have become the new bass player for the German power metal band [[Orden Ogan]] on October 16, 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rockhard.de/artikel/orden-ogan-steven-wussow-als-neuer-bassist-bestaetigt_480555.html|title=ORDEN OGAN - Steven Wussow als neuer Bassist best\u00e4tigt|publisher=Rock Hard Magazine|date=October 16, 2019|accessdate=February 9, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Discography ==\n\n=== Albums ===\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\"| Year\n! rowspan=\"2\"| Title\n! colspan=\"3\"| Peak positions\n|-\n! width=\"30\"| [[GfK Entertainment Charts|GER]]<ref name=ML/>\n! width=\"30\"| [[\u00d63 Austria Top 40|AUT]]\n! width=\"30\"| [[Schweizer Hitparade|SWI]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://swisscharts.com/showinterpret.asp?interpret=Xandria |title=Xandria |work=Hitparade.ch |publisher=Hung Medien |accessdate=5 June 2012}}</ref>\n|-\n| align=center\"| 2003 || ''[[Kill the Sun]]'' \n| align=\"center\"| 98\n| align=\"center\"| \u2014\n| align=\"center\"| \u2014\n|-\n| align=center\"| 2004 || ''[[Ravenheart]]''\n| align=\"center\"| 36\n| align=\"center\"| \u2014\n| align=\"center\"| \u2014\n|-\n| align=center\"| 2005 || ''[[India (Xandria album)|India]]''\n| align=\"center\"| 30\n| align=\"center\"| \u2014\n| align=\"center\"| \u2014\n|-\n| align=center\"| 2007 || ''[[Salom\u00e9 \u2013 The Seventh Veil]]''\n| align=\"center\"| 49\n| align=\"center\"| \u2014\n| align=\"center\"| \u2014\n|-\n| align=center\"| 2012 || ''[[Neverworld's End]]''\n| align=\"center\"| 43\n| align=\"center\"| \u2014\n| align=\"center\"| 51\n|-\n| align=center\"| 2014 || ''[[Sacrificium (Xandria album)|Sacrificium]]''\n| align=\"center\"| 25\n| align=\"center\"| 71\n| align=\"center\"| 48 \n|-\n| align=center\"| 2017 || ''[[Theater of Dimensions]]''\n| align=\"center\"| 17\n| align=\"center\"| 56\n| align=\"center\"| 25\n|}\n\n=== Compilation albums ===\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n|-\n| align=center\"| 2008 || ''[[Now & Forever \u2013 Best of Xandria]]''\n|}\n\n=== EPs ===\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n|-\n| align=center\"| 2015 || ''[[Fire & Ashes (EP)|Fire & Ashes]]''\n|}\n\n=== Singles ===\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\"| Year\n! rowspan=\"2\"| Title\n! colspan=\"1\"| Peak positions\n! rowspan=\"2\"| Album\n|-\n! width=\"30\"| [[GfK Entertainment Charts|GER]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.musicline.de/de/chartverfolgung_summary/artist/Xandria/?type=single |title=Xandria \u2014 Single-Chartverfolgung |language=German |work=Musicline.de |publisher=Phononet GmbH |accessdate=5 June 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131212025901/http://www.musicline.de/de/chartverfolgung_summary/artist/Xandria/?type=single |archive-date=12 December 2013 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n|-\n| align=\"center\" rowspan=2| 2004 || \"Ravenheart\"\n| align=\"center\" | \u2014 || rowspan=2| ''[[Ravenheart]]''\n|-\n| \"Eversleeping\"\n| align=\"center\"| 86<sup>1</sup>\n|-\n| align=\"center\" | 2007 || \"Save My Life\"\n| align=\"center\" | \u2014 || ''[[Salom\u00e9 \u2013 The Seventh Veil]]''\n|}\n<sup>1</sup> Limited edition\n\n==== Promo singles ====\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Album\n|-\n| align=\"center\" | 2003 || \"Kill the Sun\"\n| ''[[Kill the Sun]]''\n|-\n| align=\"center\" | 2005 || \"In Love with the Darkness\"\n| ''[[India (Xandria album)|India]]''\n|-\n| align=\"center\" | 2007 || \"Sisters of the Light\"<sup>1</sup>\n| ''[[Salom\u00e9 \u2013 The Seventh Veil]]''\n|-\n| align=\"center\" | 2012 || \"Valentine\"\n| ''[[Neverworld's End]]\n|-\n| align=\"center\" rowspan=\"2\"| 2014 || \"Dreamkeeper\"\n| rowspan=\"2\"| ''[[Sacrificium (Xandria album)|Sacrificium]]''\n|-\n| \"Nightfall\"\n|-\n| align=\"center\" rowspan=\"2\"| 2015 || \"Don't Say a Word\"\n| rowspan=\"2\"| ''[[Fire & Ashes (EP)|Fire & Ashes]]''\n|-\n| \"Voyage of the Fallen\"\n|-\n| rowspan=\"4\" align=\"center\" | 2017 || \"We Are Murderers (We All)\"\n| rowspan=\"4\" | ''[[Theater of Dimensions]]\n|-\n| \"Call of Destiny\"\n|-\n| \"Queen of Hearts Reborn\"\n|-\n|\"Ship of Doom\"\n|}\n<sup>1</sup> As Xandria vs. [[Jesus on Extasy]]\n\n==Members==\n===Current members===\n* Marco Heubaum \u2013 guitars <small>(1994\u2013present)</small>, keyboards <small>(1997\u2013present)</small>, vocals <small>(1994\u20132001)</small>\n* Gerit Lamm \u2013 drums <small>(2000\u2013pre